06135nam a2200805Ia 9789633865781DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20222022hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9789633865781  a(DE-B1597)633189  a(OCoLC)1337069115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aJN2191.A1bC74 2022 7aPOL0640002bisacsh04a324.2439223/eng/20220623  aMG 980862rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122877:120491 aCsanádi, Mária, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDynamics of an Authoritarian System :bHungary, 2010–2021 /cMária Csanádi, Márton Gerő, Miklós Hajdu, Imre Kovách, István János Tóth, Mihály Laki. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Metamorphosis of a Party into a System -- t1 Paths to Political Capture and Institutionalized Corruption in Hungary, 2010–2021 -- tPart II Reproduction Through Redistribution -- t2 Redistribution and Integration -- t3 Cronyism in the Orbán Regime: An Empirical Analysis of Public Tenders, 2005–2021 -- t4 Political Connectedness under Fidesz Governments and the Case of Mészáros Group of Companies -- tSummary -- tList of Authors -- tBibliography -- tSubject Index -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis conceptually synthetic and empirically rich book demonstrates the vulnerability of democratic settings to authoritarianism and populism. Six scholars from various professional fields explore here the metamorphosis of a political party into a centralized authoritarian system. Viktor Orbán and his Fidesz party needed less than ten years to accomplish this transformation in Hungary. In 2010, after winning a majority that could make changes in the constitution – two-thirds of the parliamentary seats, they evolved and stabilized the system, which produced again the two-thirds majority in 2014 and 2018. The authors reveal how a democratic setting can be used as a device for political capture. They show how a political entity managed to penetrate almost all sub-fields of the economy to arrive at institutionalized corruption, and how the centralized power structure reproduces itself. With the help of a powerful empirical apparatus—among others analyses of more than 220,000 public tenders, redistributions of state subsidies, and the interconnectedness of those privileged with the political elite — the authors detail the functioning of a crony system and the network aspects of political connections in the rapid enrichment of politically-linked businesses. Their studies demonstrate the role of political capture in this redistribution and how this capture leads to a new social stratification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAuthoritarianismzHungaryy21st century. 0aPolitical culturezHungaryxHistoryy21st century. 0aPolitical partieszHungaryy21st century. 0aPopulismzHungaryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Corruption & Misconduct .2bisacsh  aHungary.  aPolitical capture.  acrony system, redistribution, political connectedness.  ainstitutionalized corruption.  aqualitative and quantitative analysis.1 aCsanádi, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerő, Márton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGerő, Márton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHajdu, Miklós, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHajdu, Miklós, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovách, Imre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator